d 'XTKPYBREAK': module to perform CCE estimation under non-stationary common factors and multiple structural breaks in non-stationary heterogeneous panels
d
d	 xtkpybreak implements two closely related methodologies
d for non-stationary heterogeneous panels in which cross-sectional 
d   dependence is generated by a small number of unobserved common
d factors that may follow unit-root (I(1)) processes:	     1. CCE
d under I(1) factors - Kapetanios, Pesaran & Yamagata (2011,
d Journal of Econometrics) show that Pesaran's (2006)		
d Common Correlated Effects idea - proxy the unobserved factors by
d cross-section averages of the observables and add	       them
d as regressors - remains valid when the factors are I(1). The
d Common Correlated Effects Mean-Group (CCEMG) and	     
d Pooled (CCEP) estimators of the mean slope have the same limiting
d form and the same variance estimators as in the	    
d stationary case. Use xtkpybreak cce.	      2. Multiple
d structural breaks - Baltagi, Feng & Wang (2025, Econometric
d Reviews) build on KPY: because the factor proxy	    
d survives I(1) factors, unobserved factors can be treated as extra
d regressors, and breaks in slopes and in error-factor		 
d loadings become ordinary breaks in a linear regression. Break
d points are estimated jointly by least squares using the	   
d  Bai & Perron (1998, 2003) dynamic-programming algorithm; the
d regime slopes are then estimated by (partitioned) CCE.	   
d Use xtkpybreak break. 
d
d KW: panel data
d KW: structural breaks
d KW: common correlated effects
d
d Requires: Stata version 14
d
d Distribution-Date: 20260709
d
d Author:   Merwan Roudane, NA
d Support: email  merwanroudane920@@gmail.com
d
f xtkpybreak.ado
f xtkpybreak.sthlp
f xtkpybreak_break.sthlp
f xtkpybreak_cce.sthlp
f xtkpybreak_example.do
f xtkpybreak_postestimation.sthlp
